habitat_description:
The yellow-headed gecko has been introduced to Florida. Even though its numbers in the state continue to decline, established populations included Key West, Coconut Grove, and Dade County (Ashton and Ashton 1991; Lawson et al. 1991). Subspecies Notatus is native to Hispaniola, Ile a Cabrit, Ile de la Gonave, Jamaica. Also found in Grand Cayman Island. In the other hand, subspecies Fuscus is native to Central and South America. Its geographic range extends from El Salvador to western Colombia, Aruba; Curacao; Tortuga; Orchilla; Gorgona; Cuba. Both subspecies have reportedly been introduced to Florida (Lawson et al. 1991; Schwartz and Henderson 1988, 1991).

Its habitat has been described as suburban, urban, orchard, and edificarian. It is found on naval shipyards, around downtown areas, old buildings, in or under houses, around piles of brush, and on oceanside trees (Ashton and Ashton 1985; Behler and King 1979; Grant 1940; Schwartz and Henderson 1991).

Oceanside trees, piles of brush, in and under houses, and around piles of rocks and lumber.
